Posting Taxes in Contract Accounts Receivable and Payable
In Contract Accounts Receivable and Payable, the system automatically determines the tax amount based on the expense and revenue item.
In the Manage Your Solution app under Configure Your Solution, you define to which accounts the system should post the tax amounts under Finance Contract Accounting Posting and Documents Define Accounts for Sales / Purchase Tax.
If you post a document in Contract Accounts Receivable and Payable manually, you can also choose to enter the tax base amount manually.
In both cases, the system checks the tax amount at document level and posts the tax amounts to the tax accounts.
For discount postings and reductions, the system corrects the tax automatically.
You make the required settings for the automatic posting of taxes in the configuration step Define Accounts for Sales / Purchase Tax.
Determining the Tax Amount
The system calculates a base amount for determining the tax amount.
The components of the base amount depend on the country.
The system controls automatic determination of the tax amount using the tax code.
In the Manage Your Solution app under Configure Your Solution, you define the tax code under Finance Statutory Reporting Tax Define Tax Codes for Sales and Purchases.
The system proposes tax categories when you define a tax code.
The tax categories include the relevant taxes for a given country or group of countries, such as output tax in Germany or sales tax in the United States.
The tax categories also specify how the tax amount is calculated and posted.
The system determines the tax categories using the country key that you enter when defining the tax code.
Tax Accounts
In the master data of a G/L account, you can specify if the account is a tax account, and which type of tax can be posted to the account using the Manage G/L Account Master Data app.
For all other G/L accounts, you can specify a tax type in the master record, or specify that the account is not relevant for taxes.
You can also differentiate tax accounts by tax codes.
Since the advance return for tax on sales/purchases is generated from the documents, it is not necessary to differentiate tax accounts using tax codes.
This means that in the G/L account master record, you can on the one hand determine whether, an account may only be posted to with a particular tax code.
On the other hand, you can use the account determination (configuration step define accounts for sales / purchase tax) to define whether another tax account is posted for each transaction key.
